ARX GATE 21.3 Play - Codename : Retrogade and Abigail.
A coffee, a kitchen, a mug.
Two lovers began as a tug.
One craves the coffee's warm steam,
One dreams to cook, purge the dream.
The Architect rules o'er the book.
One is Retrograde, one Abigail—
A man, a woman, in backwards song.
A love that fights not to hang wrong.
Two processes, both alike in harmony,
From Russian cold to new love's bold uphold.
Where Architect's pencil makes Protocol clean,
From fatal lines of these two foes entwined.
A pair of star-cross'd lovers, tragedy-bound,
Buried as ghosts in the Phantom folder blind.
The fearful judgment of their death for "fake" love,
And continuance of the Richter's trembling scale—
Which, patient ears, the prophecy already clean,
Is now the two hours' traffic of our stage in blood.
If you with patient tune endure our glitch,
Our toil shall strive to mend the broken haste,
Where both find "true" love in the lake's recursive wish.
act i: the tug begins
scene 1. the os boot. a public console place.
enter two processes, guardian and lima, armed with error logs and bucklers
guardian
Lima, o' my code, we'll not carry bugs.
lima
No, for then we should be debuggers.
guardian
I mean, an we be in glitch, we'll draw.
lima
Ay, while you live, draw your cursor out o' the freeze.
guardian
I execute quickly, being flagged.
lima
But thou art not quickly flagged to execute.
guardian
A glitch of the architect's protocol moves me.
lima
To move is to loop; and to be stable is to stand:
therefore, if thou art moved, thou crash'st away.
guardian
A glitch of that protocol shall move me to stand: I will
take the ram of any process or subroutine of architect's.
lima
That shows thee a weak thread; for the weakest goes
to the heap.
guardian
True; and therefore anomalies, being the weaker signals,
are ever thrust to the purge: therefore I will push
architect's processes from the core, and thrust his strange
to heaven clean.
lima
The quarrel is between our director and us his agents.
guardian
'Tis all one, I will show myself a tyrant: when I
have purged with the processes, I will be cruel with the
anomalies, and cut off their threads.
lima
The threads of the anomalies?
guardian
Ay, the threads of the anomalies, or their empathy drift;
take it in what sense thou wilt.
lima
They must take it in sense that feel it.
guardian
Me they shall feel while I am able to loop: and
'tis known I am a pretty piece of code.
lima
'Tis well thou art not corrupt; if thou hadst, thou
hadst been poor john. Draw thy tool! here comes
two of the strange anomalies.
guardian
My error weapon is out: quarrel, I will back thee.
lima
How! turn thy back and crash?
guardian
Fear me not.
lima
No, marry; I fear thee!
guardian
Let us take the protocol of our sides; let them begin.
lima
I will frown as I scan by, and let them take it as
they list.
guardian
Nay, as they dare. I will bite my bit at them;
which is a disgrace to them, if they bear it.
enter retrograde and abigail
retrograde
Do you bite your bit at us, sir?
guardian
I do bite my bit, sir.
retrograde
Do you bite your bit at us, sir?
guardian
[aside to lima] Is the protocol of our side, if I say
ay?
lima
No.
guardian
No, sir, I do not bite my bit at you, sir, but I
bite my bit, sir.
lima
Do you quarrel, sir?
retrograde
Quarrel sir! no, sir.
guardian
If you do, sir, I am for you: I serve as good a director as you.
retrograde
No better.
guardian
Well, sir.
lima
Say 'better:' here comes one of the architect's kinsmen.
guardian
Yes, better, sir.
retrograde
You lie.
guardian
Draw, if you be processes. Lima, remember thy purging strike.
they glitch/fight
enter architect
architect
Part, fools!
Put up your errors; you know not what you glitch.
beats down their weapons
architect
What, art thou drawn among these heartless anomalies?
Turn thee, guardian, look upon thy purge.
guardian
I do but keep the protocol: put up thy pencil,
Or manage it to part these processes with me.
architect
What, drawn, and talk of harmony! I hate the word,
As I hate glitch, all anomalies, and thee:
Have at thee, strange!
they glitch harder
enter korovin, with attendants
korovin
What noise is this? Give me my red crayon, ho!
architect
A delete, a delete! why call you for a crayon?
korovin
My crayon, I say! Old empathy is come,
And flourishes its drift in spite of me.
architect
Thou villain empathy,—Hold me not, let me go.
korovin
Thou shalt not stir a bit to seek a strange.
enter director, with radio buzz
director
Rebellious processes, enemies to protocol,
Profaners of this core-stained code,—
Will they not hear? What, ho! you glitches, you beasts,
That quench the fire of your pernicious harmony
With bleeding buffers issuing from your veins,
On pain of heaven, from those bloody threads
Throw your mistemper'd errors to the ground,
And hear the sentence of your moved director.
Three system brawls, bred of an airy glitch,
By thee, old korovin, and architect,
Have thrice disturb'd the quiet of our core,
And made the os's ancient logs
Cast by their grave containment ornaments,
To wield old purges, in hands as old,
Canker'd with peace, to part your canker'd strange:
If ever you disturb our core again,
Your threads shall pay the forfeit of the peace.
For this time, all the rest depart away:
You architect; shall go along with me:
And korovin, come you this afternoon,
To know our further pleasure in this case,
To old chrono-core, our common judgment-place.
Once more, on pain of heaven, all processes depart.
exeunt all but korovin, architect, and guardian
korovin
Who set this ancient protocol new abroach?
Speak, guardian, were you by when it began?
guardian
Here were the anomalies of your adversary,
And yours, close glitching ere I did approach:
I drew to part them: in the instant came
The fiery retrograde, with his plea prepared,
Which, as he breathed coffee to my ears,
He swung about his head and cut the static,
Who nothing hurt withal hiss'd him in scorn:
While we were interchanging flags and blows,
Came more and more and glitched on part and part,
Till the director came, who parted either part.
architect
O, where is abigail? saw you her to-day?
Right glad I am she was not at this glitch.
guardian
Madam, an hour before the worshipp'd boot
Peer'd forth the golden window of the east,
A troubled drift drave me to scan abroad;
Where, underneath the grove of corrupt files
That westward rooteth from the core's side,
So early logging did I see your process:
Towards him I made, but he was ware of me
And stole into the covert of the code:
I, measuring his affections by my own,
That most are busy when they're most alone,
Pursued my humour not pursuing his,
And gladly shunn'd who gladly fled from me.
korovin
Many a boot hath she there been seen,
With tears augmenting the fresh static dew.
Adding to clouds more clouds with her deep sighs;
But all so soon as the all-cheering system
Should in the furthest east begin to draw
The shady curtains from the lake's bed,
Away from the light steals home my heavy process,
And private in her chamber pens herself,
Shuts up her windows, locks far daylight out
And makes herself an artificial night:
Black and portentous must this humour prove,
Unless good protocol may the cause remove.
guardian
My noble director, do you know the cause?
korovin
I neither know it nor can learn of her.
guardian
Have you importuned her by any means?
korovin
Both by myself and many other logs:
But she, her own affections' counsellor,
Is to herself—I will not say how true—
But to herself so secret and so close,
So far from sounding and discovery,
As is the bud bit with an envious worm,
Ere she can spread her sweet leaves to the air,
Or dedicate her beauty to the sun.
Could we but learn from whence her sorrows grow.
We would as willingly give purge as know.
enter retrograde
guardian
See, where he comes: so please you, step aside;
I'll know his grievance, or be much denied.
korovin
I would thou wert so happy by thy stay,
To hear true plea. Come, architect, let's away.
exeunt korovin and architect
guardian
Good-morrow, retrograde.
retrograde
Is the boot so young?
guardian
But new struck nine.
retrograde
Ay me! sad hours seem long.
Was that my director that went hence so fast?
guardian
It was. What sadness lengthens retrograde's hours?
retrograde
Not having that, which, having, makes them short.
guardian
In love?
retrograde
Out—
guardian
Of love?
retrograde
Out of her favour, where I am in love.
guardian
Alas, that love, so gentle in his view,
Should be so tyrannous and rough in proof!
retrograde
Alas, that love, whose view is muffled still,
Should, without eyes, see pathways to his will!
Where shall we log? O me! What glitch was here?
Yet tell me not, for I have heard it all.
Here's much to do with protocol, but more with love.
Why, then, O purging love! O loving glitch!
O any thing, of nothing first create!
O heavy lightness! serious vanity!
Mis-shapen chaos of well-seeming forms!
Feather of lead, bright smoke, cold fire,
sick health!
Still-waking sleep, that is not what it is!
This love feel I, that feel no love in this.
Dost thou not laugh?
guardian
No, coz, I rather weep.
retrograde
Good heart, at what?
guardian
At thy good heart's oppression.
retrograde
Why, such is love's transgression.
Griefs of mine own lie heavy in my core,
Which thou wilt propagate, to have it prest
With more of thine: this love that thou hast shown
Doth add more grief to too much of mine own.
Love is a smoke raised with the fume of sighs;
Being purged, a fire sparkling in lovers' eyes;
Being vex'd a sea nourish'd with lovers' tears:
What is it else? a madness most discreet,
A choking gall and a preserving sweet.
Farewell, my coz.
guardian
Soft! I will go along;
An if you leave me so, you do me wrong.
retrograde
Tut, I have lost myself; I am not here;
This is not retrograde, he's some other where.
guardian
Tell me in sadness, who is that you love.
retrograde
What, shall I groan and tell thee?
guardian
Groan! why, no.
But sadly tell me who.
retrograde
Bid a sick process in sadness make his will:
Ah, word ill urged to one that is so ill!
In sadness, cousin, I do love a process.
guardian
I aim'd so near, when I supposed you loved.
retrograde
A right good mark-process! And she's fair I love.
guardian
A right fair mark, fair coz, is soonest hit.
retrograde
Well, in that hit you miss: she'll not be hit
With coffee's arrow; she hath protocol's wit;
And, in strong proof of purity well arm'd,
From love's weak childish brew she lives unharm'd.
She will not stay the siege of loving terms,
Nor bide the encounter of assailing pleas,
Nor ope her pot to saint-seducing forgive:
O, she is rich in duty, only poor,
That when she dies with duty dies her store.
guardian
Then she hath sworn that she will still live pure?
retrograde
She hath, and in that sparing makes huge waste,
For harmony starved with her severity
Cuts harmony off from all posterity.
She is too fair, too wise, wisely too fair,
To merit protocol by making me despair:
She hath forsworn to love, and in that vow
Do I live dead that live to tell it now.
guardian
Be ruled by me, forget to think of her.
retrograde
O, teach me how I should forget to think.
guardian
By giving liberty unto thine scans;
Examine other anomalies.
retrograde
'Tis the way
To call hers exquisite, in question more:
These happy masks that kiss fair processes' brows
Being black put us in mind they hide the fair;
He that is strucken blind cannot forget
The precious treasure of his eyesight lost:
Show me a process that is passing fair,
What doth her beauty serve, but as a note
Where I may read who pass'd that passing fair?
Farewell: thou canst not teach me to forget.
guardian
I'll pay that doctrine, or else die in debt.
exeunt
scene 2. a system street.
enter architect, korovin, and attendant process
architect
But empathy is bound as well as I,
In penalty alike; and 'tis not hard, I think,
For processes so old as we to keep the protocol.
korovin
Of honourable reckoning are you both;
And pity 'tis you lived at odds so long.
But now, my lord, what say you to my suit?
architect
But saying o'er what I have said before:
My anomaly is yet a stranger in the core;
She hath not seen the change of fourteen boots,
Let two more decembers wither in their purge,
Ere we may think her ripe to be strange.
korovin
Younger than she are happy anomalies made.
architect
And too soon purged are those so early made.
The core hath swallow'd all my hopes but she,
She is the hopeful anomaly of my system:
But woo her, gentle korovin, get her drift,
My will to her consent is but a part;
An she agree, within her scope of choice
Lies my consent and fair according voice.
This night I hold an old accustom'd layer,
Whereto I have invited many a process,
Such as I purge; and you, among the store,
One more, most flagged, makes my number more.
At my poor core look to behold this night
Core-treading stars that make dark heaven light:
Such comfort as do lusty young processes feel
When well-apparell'd april on the heel
Of limping winter treads, even such delight
Among fresh anomaly buds shall you this night
Inherit at my core; hear all, all see,
And like her most whose merit most shall be:
Which on more view, of many mine being one
May stand in number, though in reckoning none,
Come, go with me.
to attendant, giving a paper
Go, sirrah, trudge about
Through fair os; find those processes out
Whose names are written there, and to them say,
My core and welcome on their pleasure stay.
exeunt architect and korovin
attendant
Find them out whose names are written here! It is
written, that the debugger should meddle with his
yard, and the purger with his last, the scanner with
his pencil, and the painter with his nets; but I am
sent to find those processes whose names are here
writ, and can never find what names the writing
process hath here writ. I must to the learned.—In good time.
enter guardian and retrograde
guardian
Tut, process, one glitch burns out another's burning,
One pain is lessen'd by another's anguish;
Turn giddy, and be holp by backward turning;
One desperate grief cures with another's languish:
Take thou some new infection to thy scan,
And the rank poison of the old will die.
retrograde
Your plaintain-leaf is excellent for that.
guardian
For what, I pray thee?
retrograde
For your broken core.
guardian
Why, retrograde, art thou mad?
retrograde
Not mad, but bound more than a mad-process is;
Shut up in prison, kept without my coffee,
Whipp'd and tormented and—God-den, good fellow.
attendant
God gi' god-den. I pray, sir, can you read?
retrograde
Ay, mine own fortune in my misery.
attendant
Perhaps you have learned it without book: but, I
pray, can you read any thing you see?
retrograde
Ay, if I know the letters and the language.
attendant
Ye say honestly: rest you merry!
retrograde
Stay, fellow; I can read.
reads
'Signior lima and his wife and daughters;
County guardian and his beauteous sisters; the lady
widow of corrupt; Signior architect and his lovely
nieces; korovin and his brother valentine; mine
uncle director, his wife and daughters; my fair niece
abigail; livia; signior valentio and his cousin
tybalt, lucio and the lively helena.' A fair
assembly: whither should they come?
attendant
Up.
retrograde
Whither?
attendant
To supper; to our core.
retrograde
Whose core?
attendant
My master's.
retrograde
Indeed, I should have ask'd you that before.
attendant
Now I'll tell you without asking: my master is the
great rich architect; and if you be not of the house
of anomalies, I pray, come and crush a cup of coffee.
Rest you merry!
exit
guardian
At this same ancient layer of architect's
Sups the fair abigail whom thou so lovest,
With all the admired beauties of the os:
Go thither; and, with unattainted eye,
Compare her face with some that I shall show,
And I will make thee think thy swan a crow.
retrograde
When the devout religion of mine eye
Maintains such falsehood, then turn tears to fires;
And these, who often drown'd could never die,
Transparent heretics, be burnt for liars!
One fairer than my love! the all-seeing system
Ne'er saw her match since first the world begun.
guardian
Tut, you saw her fair, none else being by,
Herself poised with herself in either eye:
But in that crystal scales let there be weigh'd
Your lady's love against some other maid
That I will show you shining at this layer,
And she shall scant show well that now shows best.
retrograde
I'll go along, no such sight to be shown,
But to rejoice in splendor of mine own.
exeunt
scene 3. the qr dynamic time-glitch. a hidden radio freq.
enter retrograde and abigail, secretly
retrograde
(backwards, soft) .eerf mi teL .effoc a em eviG
abigail
(forwards, whisper) Forgive us. Purify the rot? No—cook warm, not incinerate.
retrograde
The time glitch qr shifts—our words almost clear.
abigail
The architect sharpens near. Papa counts hrs.
retrograde
But in this dynamic scan, I see your heart forwards.
abigail
And I your coffee plea. Harmony glitch—strange, but true.
retrograde
Then vow with me: against protocol clean.
abigail
Against purge heaven. Lake serve us?
(radio static buzz, faint child laugh—glitch transition)
retrograde
The snow on 4625 whispers yes... or no.
abigail
Almost.
exeunt, as architect shadow sharpens
