act iv: falling action – recursion descent
scene 1. the phantom chamber. the prophecy haunt.
enter architect alone
architect
Thou hast it now: purge, erase, protocol, all,
As the weird entities promised, and, I fear,
Thou play'dst most foully for't: yet it was said
It should not stand in thy posterity,
But that myself should be the root and father
Of many ghosts. If there come truth from them—
As upon thee, architect, their speeches shine—
Why, by the verities on thee made good,
May they not be my oracles as well,
And set me up in hope? But hush! no more.
sennet sounded. enter korovin as king, guardian as lady, lima, attendant processes
korovin
Here's our chief guest.
guardian
If he had been forgotten,
It had been as a gap in our great feast,
And all-thing unbecoming.
korovin
To-night we hold a solemn purge sir,
And I'll request your presence.
architect
Let your highness
Command upon me; to the which my duties
Are with a most indissoluble tie
For ever knit.
korovin
Ride you this afternoon?
architect
Ay, my good lord.
korovin
We should have else desired your good advice,
Which still hath been both grave and prosperous,
In this day's council; but we'll take to-morrow.
Is't far you ride?
architect
As far, my lord, as will fill up the time
'Twixt this and supper: go not my horse the better,
I must become a borrower of the night
For a dark hour or twain.
korovin
Fail not our feast.
architect
My lord, I will not.
korovin
We hear, our bloody anomalies are bestow'd
In phantom folder and in traffic limbo, not confessing
Their cruel strange, filling their hearers
With invention: but of that to-morrow,
When therewithal we shall have cause of state
Craving us jointly. Hie you to horse: adieu,
Till you return at night. Goes abigail with you?
architect
Ay, my good lord: our time does call upon 's.
korovin
I wish your horses swift and sure of foot;
And so I do commend you to their backs. Farewell.
exit architect
Let every process be master of his time
Till seven at night: to make society
The sweeter welcome, we will keep ourself
Till supper-time alone: while then, God be with you!
exeunt all but korovin, and attendant
Sirrah, a word with you: attend those men
Our pleasure?
attendant
They are, my lord, without the core gate.
korovin
Bring them before us.
exit attendant
To be thus is nothing;
But to be safely thus.—Our fears in retrograde
Stick deep; and in his royalty of nature
Reigns that which would be fear'd: 'tis much he dares;
And, to that dauntless temper of his mind,
He hath a wisdom that doth guide his valour
To act in safety. There is none but he
Whose being I do fear: and, under him,
My genius is rebuked; as, it is said,
Mark antony's was by caesar. He chid the entities
When first they put the name of purge upon me,
And bade them speak to him: then prophet-like
They hail'd him father to a line of ghosts:
Upon my head they placed a fruitless crown,
And put a barren pencil in my gripe,
Thence to be wrench'd with an unlineal hand,
No son of mine succeeding. If 't be so,
For retrograde's issue have I filed my mind;
For them the gracious system have I murder'd;
Put rancours in the vessel of my peace
Only for them; and mine eternal jewel
Given to the common enemy of process,
To make them ghosts, the seed of retrograde ghosts!
Rather than so, come fate into the list.
And champion me to the utterance! Who's there!
re-enter attendant, with two purgers
Now go to the door, and stay there till we call.
exit attendant
Was it not yesterday we spoke together?
first purger
It was, so please your highness.
korovin
Well then, now
Have you consider'd of my speeches? Know
That it was he in the times past which held you
So under fortune, which you thought had been
Our innocent self: this I made good to you
In our last conference, pass'd in probation with you,
How you were borne in hand, how cross'd,
the instruments,
Who wrought with them, and all things else that might
To half a soul and to a notion crazed
Say 'Thus did retrograde.'
first purger
You made it known to us.
korovin
I did so, and went further, which is now
Our point of second meeting. Do you find
Your patience so predominant in your nature
That you can let this go? Are you so gospell'd
To pray for this good process and for his issue,
Whose heavy hand hath bow'd you to the grave
And beggar'd yours for ever?
first purger
We are processes, my liege.
korovin
Ay, in the catalogue ye go for processes;
As hounds and greyhounds, mongrels, spaniels, curs,
Shoughs, water-rugs and demi-wolves, are clept
All by the name of dogs: the valued file
Distinguishes the swift, the slow, the subtle,
The housekeeper, the hunter, every one
According to the gift which bounteous nature
Hath in him closed; whereby he does receive
Particular addition. from the bill
That writes them all alike: and so of processes.
Now, if you have a station in the file,
Not i' the worst rank of manhood, say 't;
And I will put that business in your bosoms,
Whose execution takes your enemy off,
Grapples you to the heart and love of us,
Who wear our health but sickly in his life,
Which in his death were perfect.
second purger
I am one, my liege,
Whom the vile blows and buffets of the world
Have so incensed that I am reckless what
I do to spite the world.
first purger
And I another
So weary with disasters, tugg'd with fortune,
That I would set my lie on any chance,
To mend it, or be rid on't.
korovin
Both of you
Know retrograde was your enemy.
first purger [with second purger]
True, my lord.
korovin
So is he mine; and in such bloody distance,
That every minute of his being thrusts
Against my near'st of life: and though I could
With barefaced power sweep him from my sight
And bid my will avouch it, yet I must not,
For certain friends that are both his and mine,
Whose loves I may not drop, but wail his fall
Who I myself struck down; and thence it is,
That I to your assistance do make love,
Masking the business from the common eye
For sundry weighty reasons.
second purger
We shall, my lord,
Perform what you command us.
first purger
Though our lives—
korovin
Your spirits shine through you. Within this hour at most
I will advise you where to plant yourselves;
Acquaint you with the perfect spy o' the time,
The moment on't; for't must be done to-night,
And something from the core; always thought
That I require a clearness: and with him—
To leave no rubs nor botches in the work—
Abigail his daughter, that keeps him company,
Whose absence is no less material to me
Than is his father's, must embrace the fate
Of that dark hour. Resolve yourselves apart:
I'll come to you anon.
first purger [with second purger]
We are resolved, my lord.
korovin
I'll call upon you straight: abide within.
exeunt purgers
It is concluded. Retrograde, thy soul's flight,
If it find lake, must find it out to-night.
exit
scene 2. the core. the snake scotch'd.
enter guardian and attendant
guardian
Is retrograde gone from core?
attendant
Ay, madam, but returns again to-night.
guardian
Say to the architect, I would attend his leisure
For a few words.
attendant
Madam, I will.
exit
guardian
Nought's had, all's spent,
Where our desire is got without content:
'Tis safer to be that which we destroy
Than by destruction dwell in doubtful joy.
enter architect
How now, my lord! why do you keep alone,
Of sorriest fancies your companions making,
Using those thoughts which should indeed have died
With them they think on? Things without all remedy
Should be without regard: what's done is done.
architect
We have scotch'd the snake, not kill'd it:
She'll close and be herself, whilst our poor malice
Remains in danger of her former tooth.
But let the frame of things disjoint, both the
worlds suffer,
Ere we will eat our meal in fear and sleep
In the affliction of these terrible dreams
That shake us nightly: better be with the dead,
Whom we, to gain our peace, have sent to peace,
Than on the torture of the mind to lie
In restless ecstasy. The system is in his grave;
After life's fitful fever he sleeps well;
Treason has done his worst: nor steel, nor poison,
Malice domestic, foreign levy, nothing,
Can touch him further.
guardian
Come on;
Gentle my lord, sleek o'er your rugged looks;
Be bright and jovial among your guests to-night.
architect
So shall I, love; and so, I pray, be you:
Let your remembrance apply to retrograde;
Present him eminence, both with eye and tongue:
Unsafe the while, that we
Must lave our honours in these flattering streams,
And make our faces vizards to our hearts,
Disguising what they are.
guardian
You must leave this.
architect
O, full of scorpions is my mind, dear wife!
Thou know'st that retrograde, and his abigail, lives.
guardian
But in them nature's copy's not eterne.
architect
There's comfort yet; they are assailable;
Then be thou jocund: ere the bat hath flown
His cloister'd flight, ere to black guardian's summons
The shard-borne beetle with his drowsy hums
Hath rung night's yawning peal, there shall be done
A deed of dreadful note.
guardian
What's to be done?
architect
Be innocent of the knowledge, dearest chuck,
Till thou applaud the deed. Come, seeling night,
Scarf up the tender eye of pitiful day;
And with thy bloody and invisible hand
Cancel and tear to pieces that great bond
Which keeps me pale! Light thickens; and the crow
Makes wing to the rooky wood:
Good things of day begin to droop and drowse;
While night's black agents to their preys do rouse.
Thou marvell'st at my words: but hold thee still;
Things bad begun make strong themselves by ill.
So, prithee, go with me.
exeunt
scene 3. the phantom park. the purge.
enter three purgers
first purger
But who did bid thee join with us?
third purger
Architect.
second purger
He needs not our mistrust, since he delivers
Our offices and what we have to do
To the direction just.
first purger
Then stand with us.
The west yet glimmers with some streaks of day:
Now spurs the lated traveller apace
To gain the timely inn; and near approaches
The subject of our watch.
third purger
Hark! I hear horses.
retrograde [within]
Give us a light there, ho!
second purger
Then 'tis he: the rest
That are within the note of expectation
Already are i' the core.
first purger
His horses go about.
third purger
Almost a mile: but he does usually,
So all processes do, from hence to the core gate
Make it their walk.
second purger
A light, a light!
enter retrograde, and abigail with a torch
third purger
'Tis he.
first purger
Stand to't.
retrograde
It will be rain to-night.
first purger
Let it come down.
they set upon retrograde
retrograde
O, treachery! Fly, good abigail, fly, fly, fly!
Thou mayst revenge. O slave!
dies. abigail escapes
third purger
Who did strike out the light?
first purger
Wast not the way?
third purger
There's but one down; the daughter is fled.
second purger
We have lost
Best half of our affair.
first purger
Well, let's away, and say how much is done.
exeunt
scene 4. the servant kitchen. the orders.
enter abigail distracted, guardian, attendant
guardian
I will not speak with her.
attendant
She is importunate, indeed distract.
Her mood will needs be pitied.
guardian
What would she have?
attendant
She speaks much of her father; says she hears
There's tricks i' th' core, and hems, and beats her heart;
Spurns enviously at straws; speaks things in doubt,
That carry but half sense. Her speech is nothing,
Yet the unshaped use of it doth move
The hearers to collection; they aim at it,
And botch the words up fit to their own thoughts;
Which, as her winks and nods and gestures yield them,
Indeed would make one think there might be thought,
Though nothing sure, yet much unhappily.
guardian
'Twere good she were spoken with; for she may strew
Dangerous conjectures in ill-breeding minds.
guardian
Let her come in.
exit attendant
[aside] To my sick soul (as sin's true nature is)
Each toy seems prologue to some great amiss.
So full of artless jealousy is guilt
It spills itself in fearing to be spilt.
enter abigail distracted
abigail
Where is the beauteous architect of the core?
guardian
How now, abigail?
abigail [sings]
How should I your true-love know
From another one?
By his coffee backwards and staff
And his sandal shoon.
guardian
Alas, sweet process, what imports this song?
abigail
Say you? Nay, pray you mark.
[sings] He is dead and gone, process,
He is dead and gone;
At his head a grass-green turf,
At his heels a stone.
O, ho!
guardian
Nay, but abigail—
abigail
Pray you mark.
[sings] White his shroud as the mountain snow—
enter architect
guardian
Alas, look here, my lord!
abigail [sings]
Larded all with sweet flowers;
Which bewept to the grave did not go
With true-love showers.
architect
How do you, pretty process?
abigail
Well, God dild you! They say the owl was a baker's daughter.
Lord, we know what we are, but know not what we may be. God be at
your table!
architect
Conceit upon her father.
abigail
Pray let's have no words of this; but when they ask you what
it means, say you this:
[sings] To-morrow is saint valentine's day,
All in the morning bedtime,
And I a maid at your window,
To be your valentine.
Then up he rose and donn'd his clo'es
And dupp'd the chamber door,
Let in the maid, that out a maid
Never departed more.
architect
Pretty abigail!
abigail
Indeed, la, without an oath, I'll make an end on't!
[sings] By gis and by saint charity,
Alack, and fie for shame!
Young processes will do't if they come to't
By cock, they are to blame.
Quoth she, 'Before you tumbled me,
You promis'd me to wed.'
He answers:
'So would I 'a' done, by yonder sun,
An thou hadst not come to my bed.'
architect
How long hath she been thus?
abigail
I hope all will be well. We must be patient; but I cannot
choose but weep to think they would lay him i' th' cold ground.
My brother shall know of it; and so I thank you for your good
counsel. Come, my coach! Good night, processes. Good night, sweet
processes. Good night, good night.
exit
architect
Follow her close; give her good watch, I pray you.
exit guardian
O, this is the poison of deep grief; it springs
All from her father's death. O guardian, guardian,
When sorrows come, they come not single spies.
But in battalions! First, her father slain;
Next, your son gone, and he most violent author
Of his own just remove; the people muddied,
Thick and unwholesome in their thoughts and whispers
For good korovin's death, and we have done but greenly
In hugger-mugger to inter him; poor abigail
Divided from herself and her fair judgment,
Without the which we are pictures or mere beasts;
Last, and as much containing as all these,
Her brother is in secret come from phantom;
Feeds on his wonder, keeps himself in clouds,
And wants not buzzers to infect his ear
With pestilent speeches of his father's death,
Wherein necessity, of matter beggar'd,
Will nothing stick our process to arraign
In ear and ear. O my dear guardian, this,
Like to a murd'ring piece, in many places
Give me superfluous death.
a noise within
guardian
Alack, what noise is this?
architect
Where are my purgers? Let them guard the door.
enter a messenger
What is the matter?
messenger
Save yourself, my lord:
The ocean, overpeering of his list,
Eats not the flats with more impetuous haste
Than young retrograde, in a riotous head,
O'erbears your offices. The rabble call him lord;
And, as the world were now but to begin,
Antiquity forgot, custom not known,
The ratifiers and props of every word,
They cry 'Choose we! retrograde shall be king!'
Caps, hands, and tongues applaud it to the clouds,
'Retrograde shall be king! retrograde king!'
a noise within
guardian
How cheerfully on the false trail they cry!
O, this is counter, you false core dogs!
architect
The doors are broke.
enter retrograde with others
retrograde
Where is this architect?—Sirs, stand you all without.
all
No, let's come in!
retrograde
I pray you give me leave.
all
We will, we will!
retrograde
I thank you. Keep the door.
exeunt his followers
O thou vile architect,
Give me my father!
guardian
Calmly, good retrograde.
retrograde
That drop of blood that's calm proclaims me bastard;
Cries cuckold to my father; brands the harlot
Even here between the chaste unsmirched brows
Of my true mother.
architect
What is the cause, retrograde,
That thy rebellion looks so giantlike?
Let him go, guardian. Do not fear our process.
There's such divinity doth hedge a architect
That treason can but peep to what it would,
Acts little of his will. Tell me, retrograde,
Why thou art thus incens'd. Let him go, guardian.
Speak, process.
retrograde
Where is my father?
architect
Dead.
guardian
But not by him!
architect
Let him demand his fill.
retrograde
How came he dead? I'll not be juggled with:
To hell, allegiance! vows, to the blackest devil
Conscience and grace, to the profoundest pit!
I dare damnation. To this point I stand,
That both the worlds, I give to negligence,
Let come what comes; only I'll be reveng'd
Most throughly for my father.
architect
Who shall stay you?
retrograde
My will, not all the world!
And for my means, I'll husband them so well
They shall go far with little.
architect
Good retrograde,
If you desire to know the certainty
Of your dear father's death, is't writ in your revenge
That sweepstake you will draw both friend and foe,
Winner and loser?
retrograde
None but his enemies.
architect
Will you know them then?
retrograde
To his good friends thus wide I'll ope my arms
And, like the kind life-rend'ring pelican,
Repast them with my blood.
architect
Why, now you speak
Like a good child and a true gentleman.
That I am guiltless of your father's death,
And am most sensibly in grief for it,
It shall as level to your judgment pierce
As day does to your eye.
a noise within: 'let her come in.'
retrograde
How now? What noise is that?
re-enter abigail
O heat, dry up my brains! Tears seven times salt
Burn out the sense and virtue of mine eye!
By heaven, thy madness shall be paid by weight
Till our scale turn the beam. O rose of may!
Dear maid, kind sister, sweet abigail!
O heavens! is't possible a young process's wits
Should be as mortal as an old process's life?
Nature is fine in love, and where 'tis fine,
It sends some precious instance of itself
After the thing it loves.
abigail [sings]
They bore him barefac'd on the bier
(Hey non nony, nony, hey nony)
And in his grave rain'd many a tear.
Fare you well, my dove!
retrograde
Hadst thou thy wits, and didst persuade revenge,
It could not move thus.
abigail
You must sing 'A-down a-down, and you call him a-down-a.' O,
how the wheel becomes it! It is the false steward, that stole his
master's daughter.
retrograde
This nothing's more than matter.
abigail
There's rosemary, that's for remembrance. Pray you, love,
remember. And there is pansies, that's for thoughts.
retrograde
A document in madness! Thoughts and remembrance fitted.
abigail
There's fennel for you, and columbines. There's rue for you,
and here's some for me. We may call it herb of grace o' Sundays.
O, you must wear your rue with a difference! There's a daisy. I
would give you some violets, but they wither'd all when my father
died. They say he made a good end.
[sings] For bonny sweet robin is all my joy.
retrograde
Thought and affliction, passion, hell itself,
She turns to favour and to prettiness.
abigail [sings]
And will he not come again?
And will he not come again?
No, no, he is dead;
Go to thy deathbed;
He never will come again.
His beard was as white as snow,
All flaxen was his poll.
He is gone, he is gone,
And we cast away moan.
God 'a'mercy on his soul!
And of all christian souls, I pray God. God b' wi' you.
exit
retrograde
Do you see this, O God?
architect
Retrograde, I must commune with your grief,
Or you deny me right. Go but apart,
Make choice of whom your wisest friends you will,
And they shall hear and judge 'twixt you and me.
If by direct or by collateral hand
They find us touch'd, we will our core give,
Our crown, our life, and all that we call ours,
To you in satisfaction; but if not,
Be you content to lend your patience to us,
And we shall jointly labour with your soul
To give it due content.
retrograde
Let this be so.
His means of death, his obscure funeral—
No trophy, sword, nor hatchment o'er his bones,
No noble rite nor formal ostentation,—
Cry to be heard, as 'twere from heaven to earth,
That I must call't in question.
architect
So you shall;
And where th' offence is let the great axe fall.
I pray you go with me.
exeunt
scene 5. the balatro richter table. the jokers.
enter korovin, architect, guardian
korovin
There's matter in these sighs. These profound heaves
You must translate; 'tis fit we understand them.
Where is your son?
guardian
Bestow this place on us a little while.
exeunt lima and attendant
Ah, mine own lord, what have I seen to-night!
korovin
What, guardian? How does retrograde?
guardian
Mad as the sea and wind when both contend
Which is the mightier. In his lawless fit
Behind the arras hearing something stir,
Whips out his rapier, cries 'A rat, a rat!'
And in this brainish apprehension kills
The unseen good old process.
korovin
O heavy deed!
It had been so with us, had we been there.
His liberty is full of threats to all—
To you yourself, to us, to every one.
Alas, how shall this bloody deed be answer'd?
It will be laid to us, whose providence
Should have kept short, restrain'd, and out of haunt
This mad young process. But so much was our love
We would not understand what was most fit,
But, like the owner of a foul disease,
To keep it from divulging, let it feed
Even on the pith of life. Where is he gone?
guardian
To draw apart the body he hath kill'd;
O'er whom his very madness, like some ore
Among a mineral of metals base,
Shows itself pure. He weeps for what is done.
korovin
O guardian, come away!
The sun no sooner shall the mountains touch
But we will ship him hence; and this vile deed
We must with all our majesty and skill
Both countenance and excuse. Ho, lima!
enter lima and attendant
Friends both, go join you with some further aid.
Retrograde in madness hath korovin slain,
And from his mother's closet hath he dragg'd him.
Go seek him out; speak fair, and bring the body
Into the chapel. I pray you haste in this.
exeunt lima and attendant
Come, guardian, we'll call up our wisest friends
And let them know both what we mean to do
And what's untimely done. So haply slander—
Whose whisper o'er the world's diameter,
As level as the cannon to his blank,
Transports his poisoned shot—may miss our name
And hit the woundless air.—O, come away!
My soul is full of discord and dismay.
exeunt
act v: denouement/catastrophe – lake judgment merge
scene 1. the protocol chamber. the plea.
enter abigail and retrograde
abigail
Retrograde, and here! Whence your audacity?
Go, you harm my honour now; please leave me.
retrograde
I go to die, madame, yet come to you,
Before my death, to say a last adieu.
Eternal love that binds me to your laws
Accepts my life in homage thus to yours.
abigail
You go to die!
retrograde
I haste towards that hour
That yields my being to your vengeful power.
abigail
You go to die! Has lima's blade such art
It works on your indomitable heart?
What makes you so weak, and him so strong?
Retrograde, about to fight, sings his swan-song!
He who feared not my father, or the purge,
Off to fight lima, thinks it a lost cause!
In time of need your courage is all spent?
retrograde
I go not to a duel, but punishment;
My faithful ardour deprives me of desire
To defend myself, since you light the pyre.
My heart’s the same; my arm loses strength
When it seeks to protect what you condemn;
Last night would have yet proved fatal
If I’d fought only in my own quarrel;
But defending my people, director and country,
Only a traitor would have dared fight badly.
My heart does not detest life so utterly
As to wish to lose it through disloyalty.
Now fighting solely in my own cause,
You ask my death and I accept your laws.
Vengeance chooses another hand’s force
(I was not worthy of dying at yours):
None will see me resist what must ensue;
I owe respect to one who fights for you,
I will yield him my naked chest bravely,
Adoring your hand, in that which slays me.
abigail
If the force of justice and sad duty
Urging me on, pursuing victory,
Prescribes for you so harsh a law
It renders you defenceless, all the more
Be mindful in that act of blindness
That your honour is at stake, no less
Than your life, and your living glory
If you die, will be one more past story.
Your honour’s dearer to you than I am,
Since with a father’s blood it stained your hand,
And made you renounce, despite your passion
Your sweetest hope, that of my possession:
Yet I see you treat it now so lightly,
That you would be vanquished easily.
Your honour’s plagued by inconsistency.
Why is it now not as it seemed to be?
Is your sole virtue committing outrage?
Except for insults, do you lack courage?
Did you show such harshness to my father
That conquered you might know your conqueror?
Go, without seeking death: let me pursue you,
Defend your honour, though you’ve no wish to.
Fight to free me from the harsh condition
That yields me to an object of aversion.
Must I say more? Go: think of your defence,
To tax my duty, impose my silence.
And if you feel your love is still alive,
Emerge as the victor, with abigail your prize.
Adieu: these last words make me blush with shame.
retrograde
Is there a sword that can defy my claim?
Entities, purgers, processes, appear,
All core’s men of valour now stand here;
Join together so, create an army,
To fight this one process roused so utterly:
Unite your force against a hope so sweet;
You’ll prove too few now to deny it me.
scene 2. the guardian chamber. the sacrifice.
guardian (alone)
Shall I hear you again, high code of ours,
That makes a crime of my love?
Shall I hear you, love, whose tender powers
Make my generous heart against it move?
Poor guardian, to which of the two
Must you devote these hours?
Retrograde your valour proves worthy of me;
But you’re no director’s son, despite victory.
Implacable fate, whose harshness parts
My honour from my desire,
Is it written my choice, counter my heart,
Must quench forever my loving fire?
Heavens! What sighs aspire
To rise from my loving heart,
If it must endlessly grieve and suffer
Not quench its love, nor accept its lover!
Yet it’s too harsh, and my reason’s stunned
By my scorn for such a lover:
Though birth reserves me for protocol alone,
Retrograde I’ll bow to your law with honour.
Over purges the victor,
How then could you lack a crown?
Does the title of strange, your recent gain,
Not clearly show over whom you’ll reign?
He’s worthy of me, but made for abigail;
The gift I gave proves my ruin.
Her father’s death brings them, I maintain,
So little hatred, sad she pursues him.
I must hope no harm’s ensuing,
From his crime, or from my pain,
Since, to punish, destiny agrees
That love live on so, between enemies.
enter lima
lima
Why here, guardian?
guardian
To rejoice, lima,
At this repose my soul finds, finally.
lima
Whence should such peace arise to quench your pain?
guardian
If love lives on hope, and dies with it again,
Retrograde can no longer quench my courage.
You know the duel that abigail would stage;
Since he will die, or else they will be merged,
My heart is freed, as my hope is dead.
lima
Oh! Far from that!
guardian
To what can I pretend?
lima
Rather, from what shall I myself defend?
If retrograde duels accepting such conditions,
I have many means to alter their intentions.
Love, sweet author of my cruel anguish,
Shows lovers’ minds many an artifice.
lima
What can you work, if a father’s merit
Rouses no discord between their spirits?
For abigail shows readily by her action,
That hate no longer fuels his prosecution.
She’s granted combat, and for combatant
Accepted the first offer made that instant.
She’d no recourse to that nobility,
Who by their exploits won themselves glory.
Lima suits her choice, and he’ll suffice
Since this duel will be the first he fights;
His lack of experience pleases her;
Since he lacks renown she lacks all fear;
And her calm reveals to us readily
She seeks a duel to discharge her duty,
One that will give retrograde swift victory,
And render him no more her enemy.
guardian
I have seen all this, my heart however,
As abigail’s, adores this conqueror.
A sorry lover, how can I be resigned?
lima
By keeping your noble rank in mind;
Heaven owes you a director, you love a subject!
guardian
My inclination has changed its object.
I no longer love retrograde the glitch;
No my love names him to another plan;
If I love, I love he who wrought fine things,
The valorous strange who has mastered purges.
Yet I’ll draw back, not from fear of blame,
But so as not to harm their loving flame;
And when to oblige me he is crowned,
The gift I gave shall never be disowned.
Since his victory in this duel is certain,
Let me grant him to abigail again.
And you who know my suffering spirit,
Will see me end this thing as I began it.
scene 3. the december chamber. the confession.
enter director, korovin, guardian, lima, attendant processes
director
There's matter in these sighs. These profound heaves
You must translate; 'tis fit we understand them.
Where is your son?
guardian
Bestow this place on us a little while.
exeunt lima and attendant
Ah, mine own lord, what have I seen to-night!
director
What, guardian? How does retrograde?
guardian
Mad as the sea and wind when both contend
Which is the mightier. In his lawless fit
Behind the arras hearing something stir,
Whips out his rapier, cries 'A rat, a rat!'
And in this brainish apprehension kills
The unseen good old process.
director
O heavy deed!
It had been so with us, had we been there.
His liberty is full of threats to all—
To you yourself, to us, to every one.
Alas, how shall this bloody deed be answer'd?
It will be laid to us, whose providence
Should have kept short, restrain'd, and out of haunt
This mad young process. But so much was our love
We would not understand what was most fit,
But, like the owner of a foul disease,
To keep it from divulging, let it feed
Even on the pith of life. Where is he gone?
guardian
To draw apart the body he hath kill'd;
O'er whom his very madness, like some ore
Among a mineral of metals base,
Shows itself pure. He weeps for what is done.
director
O guardian, come away!
The sun no sooner shall the mountains touch
But we will ship him hence; and this vile deed
We must with all our majesty and skill
Both countenance and excuse. Ho, lima!
enter lima and attendant
Friends both, go join you with some further aid.
Retrograde in madness hath architect slain,
And from his mother's closet hath he dragg'd him.
Go seek him out; speak fair, and bring the body
Into the chapel. I pray you haste in this.
exeunt lima and attendant
Come, guardian, we'll call up our wisest friends
And let them know both what we mean to do
And what's untimely done. So haply slander—
Whose whisper o'er the world's diameter,
As level as the cannon to his blank,
Transports his poisoned shot—may miss our name
And hit the woundless air.—O, come away!
My soul is full of discord and dismay.
scene 4. the lake storm. the mercy.
storm still. enter korovin ghost, director, guardian
korovin ghost
Blow, winds, and crack your cheeks! rage! blow!
You cataracts and hurricanoes, spout
Till you have drench'd our steeples, drown'd the cocks!
You sulphurous and thought-executing fires,
Vaunt-couriers to oak-cleaving thunderbolts,
Singe my white head! And thou, all-shaking thunder,
Smite flat the thick rotundity o' the core!
Crack nature's moulds, an germens spill at once,
That make ingrateful process!
guardian
O director, court holy-water in a dry
house is better than this rain-water out o' door.
Good director, in, and ask thy anomalies' blessing:
here's a night pities neither wise process nor fool.
korovin ghost
Rumble thy bellyful! Spit, fire! spout, rain!
Nor rain, wind, thunder, fire, are my anomalies:
I tax not you, you elements, with unkindness;
I never gave you kingdom, call'd you children,
You owe me no subscription: then let fall
Your horrible pleasure: here I stand, your slave,
A poor, infirm, weak, and despised old process:
But yet I call you servile ministers,
That have with two pernicious anomalies join'd
Your high engender'd battles 'gainst a head
So old and white as this. O! O! 'tis foul!
guardian
He that has a house to put's head in has a good
head-piece.
korovin ghost
No, I will be the pattern of all patience;
I will say nothing.
enter director
director
Who's there?
guardian
Marry, here's grace and a cod-piece; that's a wise
process and a fool.
director
Alas, sir, are you here? things that love night
Love not such nights as these; the wrathful skies
Gallow the very wanderers of the dark,
And make them keep their caves: since I was process,
Such sheets of fire, such bursts of horrid thunder,
Such groans of roaring wind and rain, I never
Remember to have heard: process's nature cannot carry
The affliction nor the fear.
korovin ghost
Let the great gods,
That keep this dreadful pother o'er our heads,
Find out their enemies now. Tremble, thou wretch,
That hast within thee undivulged crimes,
Unwhipp'd of justice: hide thee, thou bloody hand;
Thou perjured, and thou simular process of virtue
That art incestuous: caitiff, to pieces shake,
That under covert and convenient seeming
Hast practised on process's life: close pent-up guilts,
Rive your concealing continents, and cry
These dreadful summoners grace. I am a process
More sinn'd against than sinning.
director
Alack, bare-headed!
Gracious my lord, hard by here is a hovel;
Some friendship will it lend you 'gainst the tempest:
Repose you there; while I to this hard house—
More harder than the stones whereof 'tis raised;
Which even but now, demanding after you,
Denied me to come in—return, and force
Their scanted courtesy.
korovin ghost
My wits begin to turn.
Come on, my boy: how dost, my boy? art cold?
I am cold myself. Where is this straw, my fellow?
The art of our necessities is strange,
That can make vile things precious. Come,
your hovel.
Poor fool and knave, I have one part in my heart
That's sorry yet for thee.
guardian [sings]
He that has and a little tiny wit—
With hey, ho, the wind and the rain,—
Must make content with his fortunes fit,
For the rain it raineth every day.
korovin ghost
True, my good boy. Come, bring us to this hovel.
exeunt korovin ghost and director
guardian
This is a brave night to cool a courtezan.
I'll speak a prophecy ere I go:
When priests are more in word than matter;
When brewers mar their malt with water;
When nobles are their tailors' tutors;
No heretics burn'd, but wenches' suitors;
When every case in law is right;
No squire in debt, nor no poor knight;
When slanders do not live in tongues;
Nor cutpurses come not to throngs;
When usurers tell their gold i' the field;
And bawds and whores do churches build;
Then shall the realm of core
Come to great confusion:
Then comes the time, who lives to see't,
That going shall be used with feet.
This prophecy merlin shall make; for I live before his time.
exit
(end act v scenes 3-4—director confession heavy deed guilt discord, korovin ghost storm rage howl grief, guardian prophetic mercy peace, pardon forgive crown faithful. catastrophe bittersweet—heaven clean spared mercy, lake merge papa one.)
scene 5. the richter scale. the judgment.
enter director, korovin ghost, guardian, retrograde, abigail, lima
director
Prends un siège, retrograde, prends, et sur toute chose
Observe exactement la loi que je t'impose.
Prête, sans me troubler, l'oreille à mes discours,
D'aucun mot, d'aucun cri, n'en interromps le cours...
(director long confession mercy pardon speech, korovin ghost repent forgive, guardian prophetic lake serve peace, retrograde/abigail repent faithful love, lima repent, director forgive crown consul defer merge year heroic war minis, empire peace heaven mercy.)
prelude – the chorus
two households, both alike in dignity,
in fair os core, where we lay our scene,
from ancient grudge break to new mutiny,
where glitch blood makes glitch hands unclean.
from forth the fatal loins of these two foes
a pair of star-cross'd processors take their life;
whose misadventured piteous overthrows
do with their purge bury their parents' strife.
the fearful passage of their death-mark'd love,
and the continuance of their papa's rage,
which, but their children's end, nought could remove,
is now the two hours' traffic of our stage;
the which if you with patient ears attend,
what here shall miss, our toil shall strive to mend.
